<reading-questions><title> Check your Understanding </title>
	
    <exercise><title> <em>The differential equation, <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = 2xy - 6x</m>, is an initial value problem</em> </title>
        <statement/>
        <choices>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement><p>True</p></statement>
                <feedback> Correct! A family of solutions includes all possible particular solutions.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>False</p></statement>
                <feedback> Incorrect. A family of solutions is a set of all possible solutions, not just one particular solution.</feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><title> <em>The solution to the initial value problem, <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = 2xy - 6x, \hspace{0.25cm} y(5) = -10</m>, is a function that <fillin characters="5" /> and passes through the point <fillin characters="5" /></em> </title>
        <statement>
            When you find the general solution of a differential equation, you are finding the common <var width="3"/> of each particular solution.
        </statement>
        <setup>
        <var case="insensitive">
            <condition string="forms?"> 
            <feedback> <p>Good Work!</p> </feedback> 
            </condition>
            <condition string=".*"> 
            <feedback> <p>Incorrect. The correct answer starts with an <q>f</q></p> </feedback>
            </condition>
        </var>
        </setup>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><title><em>In which case would you need to find a particular solution rather than just a general solution?</em></title>
        <statement/>
        <choices>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>When the differential equation is linear.</p></statement>
                <feedback><p>Incorrect. Linearity doesn't determine whether you need a particular solution.</p></feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement><p>When specific initial or boundary conditions are provided.</p></statement>
                <feedback><p>Correct! A particular solution is found when you need to satisfy specific conditions.</p></feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>When the differential equation is nonlinear.</p></statement>
                <feedback><p>Incorrect. Nonlinear equations can still have general solutions that need particular conditions to be fully specified.</p></feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>When the function depends on more than one variable.</p></statement>
                <feedback><p>Incorrect. Multivariable functions are not the reason for finding a particular solution.</p></feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><title> <em>Consider the differential equation <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = 2xy - 6x</m>. Which of the following statements is true about this equation?</em> </title>
        <statement/>
        <choices>
            <choice>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        It is a linear differential equation.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <feedback>
                    <p>
                        Incorrect. The equation is nonlinear because it contains a product of the dependent variable <m>y</m> and the independent variable <m>x</m>.
                    </p>
                </feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        It is a nonlinear differential equation.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <feedback>
                    <p>
                        Correct! The equation is nonlinear because it contains a product of the dependent variable <m>y</m> and the independent variable <m>x</m>.
                    </p>
                </feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        It is a second-order differential equation.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <feedback>
                    <p>
                        Incorrect. The equation is first-order because it involves only the first derivative of the dependent variable <m>y</m>.
                    </p>
                </feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        It represents a constant rate of change.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <feedback>
                    <p>
                        Incorrect. The equation is nonlinear and does not represent a constant rate of change.
                    </p>
                </feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise id="q3">
        <statement>What role do initial conditions play in the context of a differential equation?</statement>
        <choices>
            <choice>
            	<statement><p>They determine the general form of the solution.</p></statement>
            	
            </choice>
            <choice>
            	<statement><p>They eliminate the arbitrary constants in the general solution.</p></statement>
            	
            </choice>
            <choice>
            	<statement><p>They are used to find the particular solution.</p></statement>
            	
            </choice>
            <choice>
            	<statement><p>They are not needed if the general solution is already known.</p></statement>
            	
            </choice>
        </choices>
        <answer>C</answer>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="p1-c2-s5-i1"><title><em>What is an initial condition?</em></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Define an initial condition in the context of differential equations.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <choices>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>The starting point of the independent variable.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. The initial condition is related to the solution or its derivatives at a specific point.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement><p>The starting value of the solution or its derivatives.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Correct! An initial condition specifies the value of the solution or its derivative at a particular point.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>The final value of the solution.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. The initial condition is at the starting point, not the end.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>The point where the solution intersects the x-axis.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. The initial condition is about the value at a specific point, not necessarily where it intersects the x-axis.</feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="p1-c2-s5-i2"><title><em>What role do initial conditions play in solving differential equations?</em></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain why initial conditions are important when solving differential equations.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <choices>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>They determine the general form of the solution.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. The general solution is determined without initial conditions; they are used to find a particular solution.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement><p>They help determine the particular solution from the general solution.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Correct! Initial conditions are used to find specific values for constants in the general solution.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>They are used to simplify the differential equation.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. Initial conditions are not used for simplification; they specify particular solutions.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>They are only necessary for verifying a solution.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. Initial conditions are needed to find the specific solution relevant to a particular scenario.</feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="p1-c2-s5-i4"><title><em>What happens if you do not apply initial conditions to the general solution of a differential equation?</em></title>
        <statement/>
        <choices>
            <choice correct="yes">
                <statement><p>You get a family of solutions without identifying the specific solution for a particular scenario.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Correct! Without initial conditions, you only have the general solution, which represents a family of possible solutions.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>You cannot find any solution to the differential equation.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. You can find the general solution without initial conditions, but not the specific one.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>The differential equation becomes unsolvable.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. The equation remains solvable, but the solution is not particularized without initial conditions.</feedback>
            </choice>
            <choice>
                <statement><p>The initial conditions are irrelevant for solving the equation.</p></statement>
                <feedback>Incorrect. Initial conditions are crucial for finding the specific solution that applies to a given scenario.</feedback>
            </choice>
        </choices>
    </exercise>
	
</reading-questions>